Building on what you know about functions:

**Functions you know:**
```javascript
function greet(name) {
  return 'Hello ' + name;
}
greet('Alice'); // You call it, it runs
```

**The shift for callbacks:**
- What if instead of calling a function, you *hand* it to someone else to call later?

**Simple example:**
```javascript
function doLater(myFunction) {
  // I'll call your function when I'm ready
  myFunction();
}

doLater(function() {
  console.log('I got called!');
});
```

**Why this matters:**
- Some things take time (loading data, waiting for clicks)
- You can't just wait—your program would freeze
- So you say: 'Here's what to do when you're done'

**Real example:**
```javascript
button.addEventListener('click', function() {
  console.log('Button was clicked!');
});
```

You're saying: 'Hey button, when someone clicks you, call this function.'

**Callback = function you give to someone else to call later.**

Does that click? (Pun intended)
